          <text>
            The third morning feels different.

            My muscles had adapted—still tired from walking but not the sharp soreness of day two. My body knows the rhythm now: wake, eat mushroom paste, pack up, walk.

            But this is the last time with these guides.

            Leafwhisper announced as they started, "About fifteen kilometers to the boundary—should reach it mid-afternoon. Perfect timing, actually; the Territory Two guides are already there waiting—very efficient coordination between networks."

            Rootwalker led as always—silent, steady, grounded.

            Scout bounces alongside, oblivious to approaching changes.

            The forest shifts as they walk. Subtle at first—different mosses, altered light patterns, unfamiliar bird-equivalents calling in the canopy. Then more obvious: the plant species change, network architecture adjusts, even the soil composition transitions under their feet.

            Leafwhisper noticed my attention and asked, "You can feel it? The territorial shift? It's gradual—network boundaries aren't sharp lines but transition zones where different coordination systems overlap, usually about a kilometer of blended territory before the formal boundary marker."

            I asked, "How do you know where one territory ends and another begins?"

            Leafwhisper replied, "Network protocols! Each territory maintains distinct communication frequencies and resource sharing algorithms—so when you're connected through roots or fungal links you can sense the shift in coordination patterns. It's quite distinct, actually—though I imagine it's invisible to humans who lack ground connection."

            Rootwalker said, "Marker ahead."

            ¶

            They crested a small rise, and there it was—a clearing where two massive trees grew on opposite sides, their canopies almost touching but not quite. Between them, the ground was marked with a spiral pattern of stones and flowering plants—beautiful and deliberate.

            And waiting in the clearing: two new plant beings.

            My chest tightens.

            One was tall and vine-like, deep purple-green, moving in graceful, flowing motions. The other looked almost like a walking bush—compact, dense foliage, bright orange flowers scattered throughout.

            Leafwhisper rustled—leaves animated—and said, *"There they are! Territory Two guides, right on schedule—very professional, excellent reputation. You're in wonderful hands."*

            The vine-plant moved forward; voice soft and almost musical: "Greetings. I'm Streamwalker. This is my partner, Brightbloom. We'll be guiding you through Territory Two."

            Brightbloom added, "Three days—rivers and wetlands mostly! Very different terrain from here."

            Leafwhisper rustled forward, leaves animated, and said, "She's been an excellent traveler—very good pace maintenance, asks wonderful questions, adapts quickly to new information."

            Rootwalker confirmed, "Walks well."
          </text>
