          <text>
            They reached out one root-hand and very gently touched my shoulder. Contact held for exactly two seconds—then released.

            Rootwalker said, "Good human"—highest praise possible.

            I have to look away before embarrassing tears form.

            Streamwalker gives them space—the vine-plant is clearly experienced with emotional farewells. Brightbloom bounces gently, respectful.

            Leafwhisper said finally, leaves drooping slightly, "We should go—long walk back, and you have Territory Two ahead—"

            I take a breath, then say, "Yeah. Okay."

            Buddy said softly, "Kira—your heart rate suggests emotional distress. This is normal for attachment separation—the feelings will ease."

            I say, "I know, Buddy. I know."

            Scout bounces once more between guides—old and new—then settles firmly beside me. Choice made.

            Leafwhisper and Rootwalker turn back toward Territory One's forest.

            Leafwhisper calls, already moving, "Safe travels! Tell the next guides how well you adapted—they'll be impressed!"

            Rootwalker just raises one root-hand—waves goodbye.

            Then they're gone, disappearing into the trees.

            I stand at the boundary feeling unmoored.

            Brightbloom said, "First time's always hard—saying goodbye to guides."

            Streamwalker added—not unkindly, just fact—"You'll say goodbye to us in three days too. That's how this works—temporary teams for each territory."

            I wipe my face, then say, "I know. It's just—they were good. Really good."

            Brightbloom agreed, "Leafwhisper and Rootwalker are excellent—we've worked boundary transfers with them for years. Complementary styles—very effective partnership."

            Streamwalker said, "They spoke highly of you in the coordination documentation—said you ask good questions and adapt quickly. That's valuable on long journeys."

            I manage a smile and say, "Leafwhisper would say, 'excellent adaptation capacity,' and then explain the biological mechanisms for twenty minutes."

            Brightbloom laughed—a bright chiming sound—and said, "That's absolutely accurate! Leafwhisper loves explaining things!"

            Streamwalker added, with what might have been affection, "And Rootwalker would say, 'walks good.'"

            I say, "Exactly."

            There is a pause. The boundary clearing feels liminal—between territories, between teams, between what is and what will be.

            ¶

            Streamwalker asked, "Ready to keep going?"

            I look back once more at Territory One—the forest where I'd learned to walk all day, where I started to see forests as networks, where I learned to trust guides who communicated through cascade and silence.

            Then forward to Territory Two—rivers and wetlands, new terrain, new guides, new challenges.

            The journey continues.

            I say, "Yeah—I'm ready."

            Scout bounces agreement.

            Brightbloom said cheerfully, "Excellent! Let's walk—we've got about two hours before the first river crossing; very exciting—you'll love the wetlands—completely different ecosystem from forest, much more dynamic water flow—"

            Streamwalker moves forward with flowing grace and says, "This way—the path gets softer soon. Watch your footing."
          </text>
